issing link, because Lean should automatically recognize that the key can be interpreted as `Nat`. \n\nAlternatively, perhaps we can directly see that:\n\nIn the definition of `PortMap.getIO`, `k : Key` is coerced to the type of the keys in the `AssocList`, which here is `Nat`. Therefore, the coercion from `Key` to `Nat` should work if `k.name` is a `Nat`, as in `{ inst :=_, name :=i.val }`.\n\nBut perhaps the `getIO` is actually defined to use `Key.toNat`, so it's already matching `i.val`.\n\nTherefore, it reduces to the fact that in our `AssocList`, the pair `(i.val, f ⟨i.val, h⟩)` exists, and is the first encountered in the insertion order, so it will be returned as `some (f ⟨i.val, h⟩)`.\n\nBut in this case, because `i : Fin n`, we have `i.val < n`. We need to confirm that `(RelIO.liftFinf n f)` contains `(i.val, f i)` as a pair, and that it is indeed the pair that is selected when looking for `i.val`.\n\nBut we can actually reason step by step with the proof:\n\n1. First, `fin_range n = [⟨0, _⟩, ⟨1, _⟩, ..., ⟨n-1, _⟩]`.\n2. Therefore, `List.map (λ i => (i.toNat, f i)) (fin_range n)` is `[(0, f ⟨0, _⟩), (1, f ⟨1, _⟩), ..., (n-1, f ⟨n-1, _⟩)]`. \n3. This is converted into an `AssocList`, and because `List.toAssocList` will insert in the same order, the `AssocList` will be a list of pairs where each `(i, f ⟨i, _⟩)` is inserted in order of `i`.\n4. Now, when looking up `i.val`, the first pair that matches `i.val` is `(i.val, f ⟨i.val, _⟩)`, because no previous pair has the same key (`i.val` is distinct from all `j < i.val`). Therefore, the `get?` will return `some (f ⟨i.val, _⟩)`.\n5. But because `i : Fin n`, we have `i.val < n`, and `i = ⟨i.val, _⟩`, so `f ⟨i.val, _⟩ = f i`.\n6. Therefore, `(RelIO.liftFinf n f).getIO i` is indeed `f i`.\n\nBut let's be more precise:\n\nIn the statement, we have `i : Fin n`, and we need to prove that `getIO` with `{ inst := _, name := ↑i }` is `f i`.\n\nSince `↑i : Nat` is `i.val`, the `getIO` is equivalent to looking for `i.val` in the `AssocList`.\n\nBut the `AssocList` is `[ (0, f ⟨0, _⟩), (1, f ⟨1, _⟩), ..., (n-1, f ⟨n-1, _⟩) ]` because of the order in `fin_range`.\n\nThus, when `i.val` is `k`, the pair is `(k, f ⟨k, _⟩)`, and because the list is in increasing order, the `get?` will find it in the `k`-th position (0-indexed).\n\nTherefore, the result will be `some (f ⟨k, _⟩)`, and since `i : Fin n` is `⟨k, _⟩`, then `f ⟨k, _⟩ = f i`.\n\nBut perhaps in Lean, the actual implementation of `get?` is not by order, but by searching",
